HEADWORD: Acrostic
<hw>A*cros"tic</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Gr. <?/; <?/ extreme + <?/ order, line, verse.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A composition, usually in verse, in which the first or the last
letters of the lines, or certain other letters, taken in order, form a
name, word, phrase, or motto.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A Hebrew poem in which the lines or stanzas begin
with the letters of the alphabet in regular order (as Psalm cxix.). See
<er>Abecedarian</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Double acrostic</b></col>, <cd>a species of enigma<--
crossword puzzle -->, in which words are to be guessed whose initial and
final letters form other words.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Acrostical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Acrostic</ent>⟦br⟧
